entities of the present. Levy visits a host of sites and historical figures to assemble a compelling history of social change, while seamlessly interweaving his study with personal accounts of his returns to his homeland. Central to this story is the massive migration of Jews out of Morocco. Levy traces the institutional and social changes such migrations cause for those who choose to stay, introducing the concept of “contraction” to depict the way Jews deal with the ramifications of their demographic dwindling. Turning his attention outward from Morocco, he goes on to explore the greater complexities of the Jewish diaspora and the essential paradox at the heart of his adventure—leaving Israel to return home.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aEthnologyzMoroccozCasablanca. 0aJewish diaspora. 0aJews - Morocco - Casablanca. 0aJewszMoroccozCasablanca. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  ajews, jewish, judaism, muslim, islam, muslims, israeli, israel, middle east, anthropology, anthropologist, ethnic groups, religion, religious studies, faith, belief, locale, city, region, academic, scholarly, research, educational, study, relationships, tension, conflict, morocco, africa, enlightenment, 19th century, arab, modern, contemporary, social change, migration, immigrant, demographics, diaspora, ethnology.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311069043940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226292694423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226292694/original  a978-3-11-069043-9  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles